# Phase 8: Build Caching, Log Streaming & Rollback

**Phase:** 8
**Status:** Not Started
**Depends on:** Phase 4 (Build System), Phase 5 (Deployment & Routing), Phase 6 (Dashboard)
**Blocks:** None (enhances all prior deployment functionality)

---

## Goal

Builds are significantly faster via S3-backed dependency and framework caching. Build logs stream in real-time via Server-Sent Events. Users can rollback to any of the last 10 deployments with one click. Crash-looping containers auto-rollback to the previous healthy deployment. Old Docker images are pruned automatically.

---

## Context

The platform can build and deploy apps (Phase 4-5) and display them in the dashboard (Phase 6). However, builds are slow because dependencies are installed fresh every time, build logs are only available after completion, there is no rollback mechanism, and Docker images accumulate without cleanup.

This phase addresses four cross-cutting concerns that make the platform production-ready:

1. **Build speed**: Caching node_modules and framework build artifacts in S3 eliminates redundant work. A typical Next.js rebuild with unchanged dependencies drops from ~90s to ~15s.
2. **Observability**: Streaming build logs in real-time lets the developer watch progress instead of waiting for completion. Completed logs are persisted to S3 for later retrieval.
3. **Reliability**: One-click rollback and auto-rollback on crash-loops mean the platform self-heals when deployments go wrong.
4. **Resource management**: Docker image pruning prevents disk exhaustion on the VPS.

### Why This Phase Exists

Without caching, every push triggers a full dependency install and build -- unacceptable for a platform meant to replace Vercel. Without rollback, a bad deploy means the site is down until a fix is pushed and built. Without log streaming, debugging build failures is a frustrating wait-and-read cycle. Without image cleanup, the 80 GB VPS disk fills up within weeks.

---

